item.title: [HIVE-22762] Leap day is incorrectly parsed during cast in Hive
item.description:
While casting a string to a date with a custom date format having day token before year and moth tokens, the date is parsed incorrectly for leap days.

How to reproduce

Execute 

select cast("29 02 0" as date format "dd mm rr")

with Hive. The query results in 2020-02-28, incorrectly.

Executing the another cast with a slightly modified representation of the date (day is preceded by year and moth) is however correctly parsed:

select cast("0 02 29" as date format "rr mm dd")

It returns 2020-02-29.
item.summary: Leap day is incorrectly parsed during cast in Hive

status.description: The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.

klcopp How are you creating these patches? I seem to have problems applying your patches.

apache@apache-VirtualBox:~/hive/hive$ git branch
  branch-3
  branch-3.1
* master
apache@apache-VirtualBox:~/hive/hive$ git apply HIVE-22762.03.patch
error: src/java/org/apache/hadoop/hive/common/format/datetime/HiveSqlDateTimeFormatter.java: No such file or directory
error: src/test/org/apache/hadoop/hive/common/format/datetime/TestHiveSqlDateTimeFormatter.java: No such file or directory

Got it finally, not sure why I needed to add -p0

apache@apache-VirtualBox:~/hive/hive$ git apply -p0 HIVE-22762.03.patch
Yep, I use the --no-prefix flag like the Hive wiki directs. But I hear that's not necessary anymore

// add @throws JavaDoc
private Timestamp getTimestampFromValues(List<Integer> temporalValues) {
  if (temporalTokens.size() != temporalValues.size()) {
    // use Guava Preconditions.checkState(boolean)
  }

  // Use parameters for ImmutablePair here (and removed future casts)
  List<ImmutablePair> tokensList = new ArrayList<>();

  // Instead of sorting then reversing, just sort in reverse order :)
  // https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#reverseOrder-java.util.Comparator-
  tokensList.sort((Comparator<Object>) (o1, o2) -> {
     Token token1 = ((ImmutablePair<Token, Integer>) o1).left;
      Token token2 = ((ImmutablePair<Token, Integer>) o2).left;
      return token1.temporalField.getBaseUnit().getDuration()
          .compareTo(token2.temporalField.getBaseUnit().getDuration());
    });
    Collections.reverse(tokensList);
}

Rather than adding a new token list that captures all the temporal tokens, I would rather see that the method accept a list of tokens and a list of values. The tokens can be filtered and sorted in the method. This way there is only ever a single list to keep track of and users (methods) can filter however they want on the fly.

List<String> tokens = temporalTokens.stream()
                .filter(token-> isNumericTemporalToken(token.type) || isCharacterTemporalToken(token.type))
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
